A Git tag is a reference to a specific commit â€” usually used to mark important points in the repository history, like releases, versions, or milestones.

###List all tags:
git tag

###Show detailed info for a tag:
git show v1.0

###Tagging a Specific Commit
By default, git tag tags latest commit, but you can tag any commit by its hash:
git tag -a v1.0 <commit-hash> -m "Release version 1.0"

###Pushing Tags to Remote
git push origin v1.0        # Push a single tag
git push origin --tags      # Push all tags

###Deleting a Tag
Delete locally: #git tag -d v1.0
Delete from remote: #git push origin --delete tag v1.0

###Checkout a Tag  
git checkout v1.0

###creat & checkout at atime
git checkout -b new-feature v1.0

===================================================================
#git commit --amend -m "new"
Modify the most recent commit without creating a new commit.
Can be used to:
Change the commit message
Add new changes/files to the last commit

#git commit --amend
open the editor to edit message manually
